# hilavitkutin-str, backlog

> **Type-surface reminder**: new entries use `arvo::USize` /
> `Bool` / `UFixed<N, 0, S>` instead of `usize` / `bool` / `u*`;
> `notko::Maybe` / `Outcome` instead of `Option` / `Result`;
> `hilavitkutin_str::Str` instead of `&str` / `String`. See
> `rules/type-surface.md`.

## Str layout via dedicated arvo Bitfield primitive

Str is currently a thin newtype over `arvo_bits::Bits<32>`. The
accessors (`is_const`, `is_runtime`, `id`) project the
origin-flag + reserved + ID sub-ranges in code. The designed
long-term home is a `Bitfield` primitive in arvo that carries the
named sub-ranges at type level, the packing becomes part of the
type, not the method bodies. Tracked in the arvo workspace as
task #127. When it lands, Str promotes to that primitive; the
public API (`is_const`, `is_runtime`, `id`) stays identical.

## Windows PE section walker

Current linker-section walking ships Linux (`__start_` /
`__stop_` sentinels) + macOS (`getsectiondata` on
`__DATA,hilavitkutin_strings`). Windows PE has its own section
convention (`#pragma section` + extern linker-defined symbols)
that needs a third code path. Defer until a Windows consumer
surfaces a concrete need.

## Non-64-bit platform sanity

The Str handle is u32 and the bit layout is width-neutral, but the
startup scan relies on pointer-arithmetic over linker-section
boundaries. On 32-bit targets the pointer math is identical but
needs verification. No active 32-bit consumer; defer.

## Alternative arena backings

`ArenaInterner` is a trait so hosts can pick any backing. Possible
future sibling types: `FixedArenaInterner<N>` (const-sized, no
alloc), `SlabInterner` (uses MemoryProvider slabs from
hilavitkutin-api). These ship as their own crates or
hilavitkutin-persistence features when a second consumer needs a
different backing than the one hilavitkutin supplies.

## 28-bit ID exhaustion

The 28-bit runtime ID space allows 268M entries. If a consumer
pipeline exceeds that at runtime, a follow-up round widens to a
u64 handle (reserving the extra bits for flags + larger ID space).
Current estimates keep every known consumer well under 1M runtime
strings per session, so this is not imminent.

## str_const! hardcoded ID mask

`str_const!` in `src/macros.rs` hardcodes `0x0FFF_FFFF` in two
places (the static-entry `hash` field and the returned handle
value) instead of referencing `$crate::Str::ID_MASK`. If the bit
layout ever shifts the ID width (see the 28-bit exhaustion entry
above), the macro silently desyncs from the `Str` constants.
Replace both occurrences with `$crate::Str::ID_MASK` so the
layout stays authoritative in one place.

## Bench-driven follow-ups (round 202605101036 overnight benches)

Findings index: `mock/benches/NIGHT_FINDINGS_2026-05-11.md`. Several
overnight benches touch the str interner's hot path:

**Bounds-check elision validates safe indexing in interner lookups.**
The `bounds_check` bench shows LLVM elides safe `[u8; N]` indexing
completely under const-sized arrays. The interner's lookup-table
indexing (HashEntry array, slot probing) can use safe `table[idx]`
without performance penalty as long as the table size is const-
generic. Do NOT teach interner code to reach for `get_unchecked`
or `unsafe { *ptr.add(i) }` for performance reasons; the safe form
is empirically optimal.

**Branch predictability is not a load-bearing concern in equality
checks.** The `branch_predictability` and `minmax_strategy` benches
show that branchful vs branchless code converges on aarch64 because
CSEL is the natural lowering for "select one of two values".
Str equality checks that use `if a.len() != b.len() { return false }`
guards land at the same throughput as branchless equivalents. Write
the form that reads clearest.

**load_alignment OK for inline-Str hash check.** The bench shows
aligned ptr-cast, `read_unaligned`, and `u64::from_le_bytes` all
converge on aarch64. The interner can read inline-Str payloads
via whichever shape is most ergonomic at the const-callable
boundary; no need to enforce 8-alignment on small Str payloads
for performance.

**Hash mixer choice empirically grounded.** The existing
`hash_algos` bench plus the new `rotate_strategy` finding show that
xxhash3-style fixed-rotation mixers beat SipHash-style data-
dependent-rotation mixers by ~3x on aarch64 (the data-dependent
rotation creates a dep chain across hash steps AND blocks autovec).
The str interner's hash choice should default to xxhash3-shape on
aarch64 unless SipHash's keyed-hash property is specifically
required (e.g., to defend against hash-flooding attacks from
untrusted input). For compile-time string interning where input
is trusted, xxhash3-shape wins.

Caveat: aarch64-specific. The hash mixer finding may not generalise
to x86_64; re-run before changing defaults on cross-platform builds.
